Among the other speeches in Quintus that invite examination is the tetralogy unique in epic poetry that is known as the ὅπλων κρίσις, v, 181-316. Thetis, at the conclusion of the games in honor of Achilles, calls upon the chieftain of the Achaeans that saved the body of her son to come aud receive his armon (vv. 123-7). Odysseus and Telamonian Aias rise in response and a forensis discussion is made possible. They both agree on Idomeneus, Nestor and Agamemnon as judgeS, but on the advice of Nestor these decline, and Trojan captives are assigned to decide on the claims and merits of the two contestants.
